<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n04167g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n04" href="#n04167g">N04 (VI.B.25)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n04all.htm#n04167g"> 167(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> real parish beggar / (brass badge) <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n04167g"><li>FW 210.12 </li><li><a href="../../flex/h/lexh.htm#n04167g">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/h/l39h.htm#n04167g">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n04167g">MS BL 47471b-87</ms> </li><li>JJA 48:031 <a name="h11d" href="../../ff/fdra/hda.htm#h11d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/h/h11d.htm#n04167g">Draft: I.8&sect;1.1</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"> <font color="green">[Journal of the Irish Folk Song Society]</font> I find the following note in the Editor&apos;s remarks. It is copied from the &ldquo;Cork Archaeological Journal,&rdquo; 1898. It is a copy of an entry in Kilshannig Parish Vestry Book (Mallow, Co. Cork), for May 1745:&mdash;&ldquo;At a meeting of the inhabitants of Kilshannig, the following persons, and none other, are allowed to be <mark>common beggars of this parish</mark>, and to each of them a <mark>brass badge</mark>, marked &lsquo;Parish of Kilshannig,&rsquo;, was given to be publicly worn by said beggars to distinguish them from all Foreign Beggars</mark>.&rdquo; <small> <a name="TL28jul23" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#TL28jul23"><cite title="source">The Leader</cite></a> (28 July 1923) 597/2</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
